<h2>What Is Compassion-Focused Therapy?</h2>
<p>Compassion-Focused Therapy (CFT) was developed by Professor Paul Gilbert in the 1990s specifically for people who have high levels of shame and self-criticism — and who fail to respond adequately to techniques that require self-encouragement or positive reframing, because their inner critic is too powerful to be bypassed through standard CBT techniques.</p>

<p>CFT integrates evolutionary psychology, neuroscience, attachment theory, and mindfulness with insights from Buddhist compassion practices. Its central aim is the development of compassion — for others and, crucially, for oneself — as a psychological capacity that underpins regulation, connection, and recovery.</p>

<h2>The Three Emotion Regulation Systems</h2>
<p>CFT's foundational model describes three evolutionary emotion regulation systems:</p>

<p><strong>The Threat System:</strong> Oriented to detecting and responding to danger. Produces anxiety, anger, and disgust. Essential for survival; problematic when chronically overactivated.</p>

<p><strong>The Drive/Seeking System:</strong> Oriented to achieving goals, resources, and status. Produces motivation, excitement, and pleasure. Produces anxiety and shame when goals aren't met.</p>

<p><strong>The Contentment/Affiliation/Soothing System:</strong> Oriented to connection, safety, and rest. Produces feelings of warmth, safeness, and belonging. This system is chronically underactivated in people with high shame and self-criticism — often because it was associated with threat or neglect in early attachment experiences.</p>

<p>CFT works to rebalance these systems — reducing threat-system reactivity and developing the soothing system's capacity through compassion cultivation.</p>

<h2>Why Self-Criticism Is So Damaging</h2>
<p>Self-criticism activates the same threat system as external threat. The inner critic — the voice that says "you're stupid," "you're worthless," "you always fail" — generates genuine physiological threat responses: cortisol release, sympathetic activation, the same neurobiological pattern as being attacked. This is why self-criticism doesn't motivate; it activates threat and reduces the access to the resources needed to actually perform or change.</p>

<h2>What CFT Techniques Look Like</h2>

<h3>Developing the Compassionate Mind</h3>
<p>CFT involves a significant component of exercises aimed at building the experience of compassion — not as an intellectual concept but as a felt sense. This includes imagining a compassionate figure (a person, a nature scene, an archetype) that embodies wisdom, warmth, and non-judgment; and gradually internalising this perspective.</p>

<h3>Compassionate Self</h3>
<p>A key CFT technique is developing access to the "compassionate self" — the aspect of you that can respond to your own suffering with the same care you would give to someone you love. This is often deeply unfamiliar for people with high shame, and practising it is the central work of CFT.</p>

<h3>Soothing Rhythm Breathing and Mindfulness</h3>
<p>CFT uses specific practices to activate the parasympathetic nervous system and the soothing/affiliation system — slow rhythmic breathing, grounding in the senses, mindful awareness of the present moment.</p>

<h2>Who Benefits Most from CFT</h2>
<p>CFT is particularly effective for people with:</p>
<ul>
  <li>High shame and self-criticism (the primary target population)</li>
  <li>Depression with significant self-attacking patterns</li>
  <li>Eating disorders with intense body-related shame</li>
  <li>Complex trauma and developmental trauma with internalised badness</li>
  <li>BPD and self-harm with shame-driven patterns</li>
  <li>People who "know" they shouldn't self-criticise but can't stop</li>
</ul>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>Isn't self-compassion just making excuses for yourself?</strong><br/>
Research shows the opposite. Self-compassion is associated with higher motivation, better recovery from failure, greater accountability, and better wellbeing. The fear that self-compassion will make you lazy or complacent is not supported by evidence.</p>

<p><strong>What's the difference between CFT and mindfulness?</strong><br/>
Mindfulness is a component of CFT but CFT adds the warm, compassionate quality to mindful awareness. You can be mindfully aware of your suffering without compassionate response; CFT adds the element of caring about what you observe.</p>

